that was taught
on the sh ow.

253
00:12:28,681 --> 00:12:30,080
[indistinct]

254
00:12:30,149 --> 00:12:34,882
GATES: "Soul Train" made
black culture truly national

255
00:12:34,954 --> 00:12:37,752
and kept it accessible
to the African Americans

256
00:12:37,823 --> 00:12:41,384
who were moving out of their old
segregated neighborhoods

257
00:12:41,460 --> 00:12:45,226
and integrating white suburbs
for the first time.

258
00:12:45,297 --> 00:12:49,927
°Ashes, ashes,
we all fall down <i>°</i>

259
00:12:50,002 --> 00:12:53,096
Professional opportunities
were opening up,

260
00:12:53,172 --> 00:12:56,733
both in civil service
and in the private sector,

261
00:12:56,809 --> 00:12:59,642
spurring the growth
of the black middle class.

262
00:12:59,712 --> 00:13:04,911
The American dream was finally
coming within reach for some

263
00:13:04,984 --> 00:13:09,114
thanks to a new idea
called Affirmative Action,

264
00:13:09,188 --> 00:13:11,782
which prescribed
concrete policies

265
00:13:11,857 --> 00:13:14,587
to end historic
discrimination.

266
00:13:14,660 --> 00:13:16,992
You cannot explain
the significant increase

267
00:13:17,062 --> 00:13:20,122
of middle-class blacks
in professional positions

268
00:13:20,199 --> 00:13:22,292
and in colleges
and universities

269
00:13:22,368 --> 00:13:26,304
without taking account
of these civil rights acts

270
00:13:26,372 --> 00:13:28,135
and Affirmative Action programs.

271
00:13:28,207 --> 00:13:31,176
It definitely
improved their life.

272
00:13:31,243 --> 00:13:32,574
You and I
are prime examples.

273
00:13:32,645 --> 00:13:33,771
Precisely, yeah.

274
00:13:40,052 --> 00:13:43,317
GATES: In September 1969,

275
00:13:43,389 --> 00:13:46,324
I drove to New Haven,
Connecticut,

276
00:13:46,392 --> 00:13:50,829
a world away from my hometown,
Piedmont, West Virginia.

277
00:13:50,896 --> 00:13:54,832
I was one of the lucky
96 black students

278
00:13:54,900 --> 00:13:57,460
starting at Yale that fall,

279
00:13:57,536 --> 00:14:01,495
a huge leap
from the 6 black men

280
00:14:01,574 --> 00:14:04,509
who had graduated
in the class of '66,

281
00:14:04,577 --> 00:14:06,738
just 3 years earlier.

282
00:14:06,812 --> 00:14:09,337
Yale's president,
Kingman Brewster,

283
00:14:09,415 --> 00:14:11,849
who had made
the bold decision

284
00:14:11,917 --> 00:14:14,181
to open up
admissions policies,

285
00:14:14,253 --> 00:14:18,713
greeted us with a speech
I'll never forget.

286
00:14:18,791 --> 00:14:20,349
He said,
"Welcome to Yale.

287
00:14:20,426 --> 00:14:22,189
"You're among
the intellectual elect.

288
00:14:22,261 --> 00:14:25,856
"You are one of the 1,000
male leaders

289
00:14:25,931 --> 00:14:29,628
brought into
the freshman class."

290
00:14:29,702 --> 00:14:33,763
Our goal,
our revolutionary action

291
00:14:33,839 --> 00:14:38,299
would be to integrate
the white power elite.

292
00:14:38,377 --> 00:14:42,040
The other black students
I met at Yale were brilliant,

293
00:14:42,114 --> 00:14:45,811
including future neurosurgeon
Dr. Ben Carson,

294
00:14:45,885 --> 00:14:48,877
future United States
Congresswoman

295
00:14:48,954 --> 00:14:50,854
Sheila Jackson Lee,

296
00:14:50,923 --> 00:14:53,391
and Kurt Schmoke,
who would go on to become

297
00:14:53,459 --> 00:14:56,053
the first black mayor
of Baltimore.

298
00:14:56,128 --> 00:14:58,790
SCHMOKE: I thought of
our class coming in

299
00:14:58,864 --> 00:15:01,833
as pan of what Dr. King
was talking about,

300
00:15:01,901 --> 00:15:04,392
certainly what my grandmother
would wish for,

301
00:15:04,470 --> 00:15:06,904
you know, that these
institutions were opening up

302
00:15:06,972 --> 00:15:09,031
to African Americans.

303
00:15:09,108 --> 00:15:12,339
Uh, somewhere in here.

304
00:15:12,411 --> 00:15:13,742
Where's the mark?

305
00:15:13,812 --> 00:15:15,211
There you go.

306
00:15:15,281 --> 00:15:17,215
Affirmative Action,
for us,

307
00:15:17,283 --> 00:15:21,219
was the first chance
we had to compete

308
00:15:21,287 --> 00:15:23,221
with white boys,
our peers,

309
00:15:23,289 --> 00:15:24,654
on a level
playing field.

310
00:15:24,723 --> 00:15:27,089
You know, I never
considered myself

311
00:15:27,159 --> 00:15:29,423
as being unqualified.
Right.

312
00:15:29,495 --> 00:15:31,429
This was all about
inclusion.

313
00:15:31,497 --> 00:15:35,695
This was about me being
a pan of and not apart from.

314
00:15:35,768 --> 00:15:37,759
GATES: Integrating
the power elite

315
00:15:37,836 --> 00:15:40,361
was just the beginning.

316
00:15:40,439 --> 00:15:44,739
For us, black power meant
shaping Yale to meet our needs,

317
00:15:44,810 --> 00:15:46,937
forming a black
student alliance,

318
00:15:47,012 --> 00:15:48,946
and demanding new classes

319
00:15:49,014 --> 00:15:53,110
emphasizing African American
history and culture.

320
00:15:59,291 --> 00:16:02,283
But off campus,
the assertive stance

321
00:16:02,361 --> 00:16:05,455
of the black power movement
had aroused fears,

322
00:16:05,531 --> 00:16:10,059
fears that began to take
tangible form.

323
00:16:11,537 --> 00:16:14,472
Calling the Panthers
"the greatest threat

324
00:16:14,540 --> 00:16:16,974
to the internal security
of the country,"

325
00:16:17,042 --> 00:16:19,476
the FBI launched
a secret campaign

326
00:16:19,545 --> 00:16:24,573
of surveillance, infiltration,
and disinformation

327
00:16:24,650 --> 00:16:29,110
aimed at seeding conﬂict
between the black power groups.

328
00:16:29,188 --> 00:16:32,157
Were you aware of this
counterintelligence program

329
00:16:32,224 --> 00:16:33,691
as it was going on?

330
00:16:33,759 --> 00:16:35,784
We thought
they wanted to kill us.

331
00:16:35,861 --> 00:16:37,726
What we didn't understand
is really

332
00:16:37,796 --> 00:16:40,697
what they wanted to do
was confuse us,

333
00:16:40,766 --> 00:16:43,326
to make us think our friends
were our enemies,

334
00:16:43,402 --> 00:16:45,597
to make us lose confidence
in what we were doing.

335
00:16:45,671 --> 00:16:48,299
Why would the FBI care

336
00:16:48,374 --> 00:16:51,673
about the handful
of black people wearing berets

337
00:16:51,744 --> 00:16:54,440
and the handful of
black people in dashikis?

338
00:16:54,513 --> 00:16:55,844
You know, these
were not mass movements

339
00:16:55,914 --> 00:16:57,176
where 20 million
black people,

340
00:16:57,249 --> 00:16:58,580
you know, lined up
to join them.

341
00:16:58,650 --> 00:17:01,380
Nobody really was threatened
by the Panthers.

342
00:17:01,453 --> 00:17:02,818
Let's be honest.

343
00:17:02,888 --> 00:17:04,856
Hoover wasn't
afraid of them,

344
00:17:04,923 --> 00:17:07,391
and he wasn't
afraid of us.

345
00:17:07,459 --> 00:17:09,689
He feared us
in our unity,

346
00:17:09,762 --> 00:17:12,492
the potential of a unified
black movement,

347
00:17:12,564 --> 00:17:14,862
self-conscious and armed.

348
00:17:14,933 --> 00:17:18,369
GATES: In March 1972,

349
00:17:18,437 --> 00:17:22,373
over 8,000 people,
including Cultural Nationalists,

350
00:17:22,441 --> 00:17:26,537
Black Panthers, representatives
of the black arts movement,

351
00:17:26,612 --> 00:17:28,637
mainstream civil rights
activists,

352
00:17:28,714 --> 00:17:30,875
and elected officials
come together

353
00:17:30,949 --> 00:17:35,648
in Gary, Indiana, intent on
defining a unified agenda

354
00:17:35,721 --> 00:17:39,282
through the first national
black political convention.

355
00:17:41,126 --> 00:17:43,117
What was the idea
behind this meeting?

356
00:17:43,195 --> 00:17:46,790
There was a recognition that
protect politics wasn't enough.

357
00:17:46,865 --> 00:17:49,891
You actually have to
struggle for power.

358
00:17:49,968 --> 00:17:51,731
MAN: All right,
please, please, please.

359
00:17:51,804 --> 00:17:54,898
In the interest--
Please. Now let's go.

360
00:17:54,973 --> 00:17:56,964
KELLEY: One of the things
that Gary did reveal, though,

361
00:17:57,042 --> 00:18:00,239
is that unity
is a hard thing.

362
00:18:00,312 --> 00:18:02,075
MAN:The political agenda

363
00:18:02,147 --> 00:18:03,580
that comes out
of this convention

364
00:18:03,649 --> 00:18:05,708
has to be a nearly
unanimous document.

365
00:18:05,784 --> 00:18:08,082
If it's not, it will
simply be ignored

366
00:18:08,153 --> 00:18:09,677
by the major
political parties.

367
00:18:09,755 --> 00:18:11,518
"Why is it that you all
don't agree?"

368
00:18:11,590 --> 00:18:12,648
Yeah.

369
00:18:12,724 --> 00:18:14,487
We have never had that
in the black community,

370
00:18:14,560 --> 00:18:17,757
and it has never been true
in the white community.

371
00:18:17,830 --> 00:18:19,798
But only we are
asked about it.

372
00:18:19,865 --> 00:18:21,127
Ha ha ha.

373
00:18:21,200 --> 00:18:23,930
Going and participating
did not necessarily mean

374
00:18:24,002 --> 00:18:25,367
that you agree
with everything,

375
00:18:25,437 --> 00:18:28,065
but not to be there

376
00:18:28,140 --> 00:18:31,541
to witness this
and to be a pan of it

377
00:18:31,610 --> 00:18:34,977
would have been,
for me, irresponsible.

378
00:18:35,047 --> 00:18:36,742
All in favor
of adopting

379
00:18:36,815 --> 00:18:38,612
the National Black Agenda

380
00:18:38,684 --> 00:18:42,120
please signify
by raising your hands!

381
00:18:42,187 --> 00:18:46,123
GATES: The participants united
across ideological lines

382
00:18:46,191 --> 00:18:49,126
around the black community's
most crucial issue,

383
00:18:49,194 --> 00:18:51,128
the longstanding
economic inequality

384
00:18:51,196 --> 00:18:55,132
that the civil rights movement
hadn't been able to eradicate.

385
00:18:55,200 --> 00:18:57,930
JACKSON: Now we find ourselves
with the right

386
00:18:58,003 --> 00:19:01,131
to move in any neighborhood
in America,

387
00:19:01,206 --> 00:19:04,300
and we can't pay the note.

388
00:19:04,376 --> 00:19:08,472
We have the right to go
to any school in America.

389
00:19:08,547 --> 00:19:11,311
We can't pay the tuition.

390
00:19:11,383 --> 00:19:15,319
We've got the right
to buy any car in America.

391
00:19:15,387 --> 00:19:18,151
<i>But we can't stop</i> it
<i>from being repossessed.</i>

392
00:19:18,223 --> 00:19:21,659
We are not arguing about
our Constitutionality.

393
00:19:21,727 --> 00:19:24,321
We are raising
a basic question--

394
00:19:24,396 --> 00:19:29,265
when will we get paid for
the work we have already done?

395
00:19:29,334 --> 00:19:31,461
[Cheering and applause]

396
00:19:37,242 --> 00:19:39,938
BLACKWELL: In the Seventies,
we really had

397
00:19:40,012 --> 00:19:42,173
a tale of three cities.

398
00:19:42,247 --> 00:19:45,341
We have a few African Americans
who have achieved

399
00:19:45,417 --> 00:19:48,511
real greatness
in terms of education,

400
00:19:48,587 --> 00:19:51,181
in business, in politics.

401
00:19:51,256 --> 00:19:54,316
Then you had
a black middle class

402
00:19:54,393 --> 00:19:57,851
that had middle-class status,
middle-class ideals,

403
00:19:57,930 --> 00:20:00,364
did not quite have
middle-class stability,

404
00:20:00,432 --> 00:20:02,866
but middle class nonetheless.

405
00:20:02,935 --> 00:20:06,701
And then you had a huge swath
of the black community

406
00:20:06,772 --> 00:20:07,898
that was poor,

407
00:20:07,973 --> 00:20:09,770
and its poverty
was worse

408
00:20:09,841 --> 00:20:12,571
than the poverty
that preceded it.

409
00:20:17,616 --> 00:20:20,710
GATES: During that time,
larger economic forces

410
00:20:20,786 --> 00:20:24,381
were reshaping
the American landscape.

411
00:20:24,456 --> 00:20:27,721
Industries were moving out
of the inner cities.

412
00:20:27,793 --> 00:20:30,557
White people
and African Americans

413
00:20:30,629 --> 00:20:32,722
who had made it
into the middle class

414
00:20:32,798 --> 00:20:35,266
followed the jobs
to the suburbs.

415
00:20:35,334 --> 00:20:39,134
The black poor
were left behind.

416
00:20:39,204 --> 00:20:41,672
There's a big
difference, Skip,

417
00:20:41,740 --> 00:20:44,038
between neighborhoods

418
00:20:44,109 --> 00:20:47,545
in which a majority
of the adults are working,

419
00:20:47,613 --> 00:20:50,241
like was the case,
say, back in 1950...

420
00:20:50,315 --> 00:20:51,612
Mm-hmm.

421
00:20:51,683 --> 00:20:54,243
And neighborhoods
in which a significant

422
00:20:54,319 --> 00:20:56,617
majority of the adults
are not working.

423
00:20:56,688 --> 00:21:00,180
Joblessness triggers problems
in a neighborhood-

424
00:21:00,259 --> 00:21:04,252
family breakups,
drug trafficking, gangs.

425
00:21:04,329 --> 00:21:06,024
What you're describing

426
00:21:06,098 --> 00:21:08,589
is a perfect storm
for disaster

427
00:21:08,667 --> 00:21:11,727
for the poorest element
of the African
American community.

428
00:21:11,803 --> 00:21:13,100
Yeah, absolutely.

429
00:21:13,171 --> 00:21:14,900
Well, what strikes me
as a paradox

430
00:21:14,973 --> 00:21:16,907
is that all this
occurred

431
00:21:16,975 --> 00:21:19,307
precisely as black
people were gaining

432
00:21:19,378 --> 00:21:24,577
increasing political
power and efficacy
in the cities.

433
00:21:24,650 --> 00:21:28,609
Being mayor of Gary
has not made it possible

434
00:21:28,687 --> 00:21:31,781
for me to control
things like jobs

435
00:21:31,857 --> 00:21:34,758
and the economic conditions
of black people.

436
00:21:34,826 --> 00:21:38,353
[Applause]

437
00:21:38,430 --> 00:21:41,957
The unemployment rate
is 4 and 5 times greater

438
00:21:42,034 --> 00:21:45,128
than the national unemployment
rate during the Depression.

439
00:21:45,203 --> 00:21:47,228
[Applause]

440
00:21:47,639 --> 00:21:50,130
Congratulations, Mr. Mayor.

441
00:21:50,208 --> 00:21:53,405
GATES: When my old friend from
Yale, Kurt Schmoke, was elected,

442
00:21:53,478 --> 00:21:57,244
he, like the country's
other black mayors,

443
00:21:57,316 --> 00:21:59,648
inherited a city
in decline

444
00:21:59,718 --> 00:22:02,414
and abandoned
by the Federal government.

445
00:22:02,487 --> 00:22:06,856
SCHMOKE: When I became mayor,
it was clear that we had

446
00:22:06,925 --> 00:22:10,486
significant problems in
the African American community

447
00:22:10,562 --> 00:22:13,292
that weren't being faced
in the white community.

448
00:22:13,365 --> 00:22:15,663
I didn't realize,
however,

449
00:22:15,734 --> 00:22:19,261
that the other thing
that I was gonna face

450
00:22:19,338 --> 00:22:21,465
was the negative impacts
of the war on drugs.

451
00:22:21,540 --> 00:22:25,499
NEWSMAN: President Reagan signed
a stiff new anti-drug law

452
00:22:25,577 --> 00:22:29,513
authorizing $1.7 billion
to fight drug abuse.

453
00:22:29,581 --> 00:22:30,775
REAGAN : The American people
want their government

454
00:22:30,849 --> 00:22:32,714
to get tough
and go on the offensive,

455
00:22:32,784 --> 00:22:34,911
And that's exactly
what we intend.

456
00:22:39,958 --> 00:22:41,949
ALEXANDER: From the outset,
the war on drugs

457
00:22:42,027 --> 00:22:46,123
had relatively little to do
with genuine concern

458
00:22:46,198 --> 00:22:49,065
about people struggling with
drug addiction and drug abuse...

459
00:22:49,134 --> 00:22:51,728
ANNOUNCER: This is
your brain on drugs.

460
00:22:51,803 --> 00:22:53,930
And much to do
with politics...

461
00:22:54,005 --> 00:22:55,029
Just say no.

462
00:22:55,107 --> 00:22:56,540
Racial politics,

463
00:22:56,608 --> 00:23:01,568
using racially coded get-tough
political peals on issues

464
00:23:01,646 --> 00:23:03,807
of crime and welfare

465
00:23:03,882 --> 00:23:07,147
in order to appeal to poor
and working-class whites

466
00:23:07,219 --> 00:23:09,653
who are anxious about
and resentful of

467
00:23:09,721 --> 00:23:12,656
many of the gains
of African Americans

468
00:23:12,724 --> 00:23:14,487
in the civil rights movement.

469
00:23:23,368 --> 00:23:26,166
GATES: That war on drugs
would be waged

470
00:23:26,238 --> 00:23:28,001
in African American
neighborhoods

471
00:23:28,073 --> 00:23:32,169
like Harlem's Wagner Houses,
where Terrence Stevens grew up.

472
00:23:32,244 --> 00:23:34,678
Were you aware
that the government

473
00:23:34,746 --> 00:23:36,839
had declared
a war on drugs?

474
00:23:36,915 --> 00:23:38,507
I knew that there was
a war on drugs

475
00:23:38,583 --> 00:23:39,982
in the street
with law enforcement

476
00:23:40,051 --> 00:23:41,985
because I remember,
as a kid,

477
00:23:42,053 --> 00:23:44,578
we'd just be hanging out
in front of our buildings,

478
00:23:44,656 --> 00:23:46,021
and the police
would come

479
00:23:46,091 --> 00:23:47,524
and just throw everybody
up on the wall

480
00:23:47,592 --> 00:23:48,889
and started
checking everybody.

481
00:23:48,960 --> 00:23:50,518
They're running up
in these apartment buildings

482
00:23:50,595 --> 00:23:51,789
with their guns out.

483
00:23:51,863 --> 00:23:55,060
It had a devastating effect
on the black community.

484
00:23:56,768 --> 00:23:58,292
GATES: In the mid-1980's,

485
00:23:58,370 --> 00:24:01,305
inner-city neighborhoods
like Terrence's,

486
00:24:01,373 --> 00:24:05,036
which were already struggling
to combat poverty and decay,

487
00:24:05,110 --> 00:24:07,544
suffered a staggering blow.

488
00:24:07,612 --> 00:24:10,206
STEVENS: Crack stole
the sh ow.

489
00:24:10,282 --> 00:24:13,046
Crack just like
killed the game.

490
00:24:13,118 --> 00:24:15,052
It was indescribable,

491
00:24:15,120 --> 00:24:17,714
the level of hardships
and whatnot

492
00:24:17,789 --> 00:24:20,189
that, you know,
people was experiencing.

493
00:24:20,258 --> 00:24:24,422
They would be smoking
crack cocaine in a park.

494
00:24:24,496 --> 00:24:26,396
You know, people
literally stealing TV's

495
00:24:26,465 --> 00:24:27,932
out of your house,
you know.

496
00:24:27,999 --> 00:24:32,834
Crack really hit
Harlem heavy.

497
00:24:32,904 --> 00:24:34,997
The war on drugs
is focused on crack.

498
00:24:35,073 --> 00:24:36,062
Let's go.

499
00:24:36,141 --> 00:24:37,870
[Men shouting]

500
00:24:37,943 --> 00:24:39,103
Police!

501
00:24:43,148 --> 00:24:45,241
ALEXANDER: When crack
hit the streets,

502
00:24:45,317 --> 00:24:48,946
The Reagan administration
seized on this development,

503
00:24:49,020 --> 00:24:52,251
actually hiring staff
whose job it was

504
00:24:52,324 --> 00:24:55,088
to publicize
inner-city crack babies...

505
00:24:55,160 --> 00:24:56,184
