00:37:34,752 --> 00:37:38,347
BLACKWELL: The government's
failure to respond

751
00:37:38,422 --> 00:37:40,686
I don't think was just because
people were black

752
00:37:40,758 --> 00:37:43,022
or just because
people were poor.

753
00:37:43,094 --> 00:37:45,028
People were left
in that crisis

754
00:37:45,096 --> 00:37:47,997
because they were
black and poor.

755
00:37:49,533 --> 00:37:53,060
It was strictly because
they did not matter.

756
00:38:05,783 --> 00:38:08,217
GATES: A few days
after the ﬂoods,

757
00:38:08,286 --> 00:38:12,552
an official delegation visited
Katrina evacuees

758
00:38:12,623 --> 00:38:15,091
sheltered in
the Houston Astrodome.

759
00:38:15,159 --> 00:38:18,560
Among them was the sole
African American

760
00:38:18,629 --> 00:38:22,395
in the United States Senate,
Barack Obama,

761
00:38:22,466 --> 00:38:25,401
the junior Senator
from Illinois.

762
00:38:25,469 --> 00:38:28,996
OBAMA: The people of New Orleans
weren't just abandoned

763
00:38:29,073 --> 00:38:30,938
during the hurricane.

764
00:38:31,008 --> 00:38:33,408
They were abandon ed
long ago

765
00:38:33,477 --> 00:38:35,741
to murder and mayhem
in their streets,

766
00:38:35,813 --> 00:38:38,748
to substandard schools,
to dilapidated housing,

767
00:38:38,816 --> 00:38:41,910
to inadequate health care,

768
00:38:41,986 --> 00:38:45,422
to a pervasive sense
of hopelessness.

769
00:38:45,489 --> 00:38:49,482
Now, that's the deeper shame
of this past week.

770
00:38:53,497 --> 00:38:55,624
Thank you, everybody.
God bless you.

771
00:38:55,700 --> 00:38:58,191
GATES: Just a year
and a half later,

772
00:38:58,269 --> 00:39:00,362
Obama announced
that he would seek

773
00:39:00,438 --> 00:39:03,965
the Democratic nomination for
the United States Presidency.

774
00:39:04,041 --> 00:39:08,034
It was an audacious decision
for any first-term Senator,

775
00:39:08,112 --> 00:39:11,604
but especially
for an African American.

776
00:39:11,682 --> 00:39:13,377
One day there may be
a black President,

777
00:39:13,451 --> 00:39:17,854
but there will never be a black
President named Barack Obama.

778
00:39:17,922 --> 00:39:20,891
Ladies and gentlemen,
that's too black.

779
00:39:20,958 --> 00:39:22,050
When I did the joke,

780
00:39:22,126 --> 00:39:23,184
I really didn't believe
he could be President.

781
00:39:23,260 --> 00:39:24,488
It was about me
sort of just saying

782
00:39:24,562 --> 00:39:26,086
the country wasn't ready.

783
00:39:26,163 --> 00:39:28,563
GATES: Many African Americans
simply didn't believe

784
00:39:28,632 --> 00:39:31,226
that Obama could
persuade white voters

785
00:39:31,302 --> 00:39:35,568
to elect a black man
to the nation's highest office.

786
00:39:35,639 --> 00:39:37,072
[Cheering]

787
00:39:37,141 --> 00:39:39,109
Oh, I think
that's a good one!
That's a good one!

788
00:39:39,176 --> 00:39:40,643
But as the months went by,

789
00:39:40,711 --> 00:39:44,909
his unprecedented confidence
began to pay off.

790
00:39:44,982 --> 00:39:48,247
This fall, we owe the American
people a real choice.

791
00:39:48,319 --> 00:39:49,547
[Cheering and applause]

792
00:39:49,620 --> 00:39:51,588
GATES: The campaign's
freshest face

793
00:39:51,655 --> 00:39:53,953
has now emerged
as its frontrunner.

794
00:39:54,024 --> 00:39:57,118
What do we really know
about Barack Obama?

795
00:39:57,194 --> 00:39:59,754
MAN: The reason that he's
considered such a big deal

796
00:39:59,830 --> 00:40:01,923
is simply
because he's black.

797
00:40:01,999 --> 00:40:03,364
Do we really want somebody
like that in the White House?

798
00:40:03,434 --> 00:40:05,925
Here's a candidate
who claims to be a unifier,

799
00:40:06,003 --> 00:40:08,597
and yet he belongs
to a church

800
00:40:08,672 --> 00:40:11,300
where they specialize
in denouncing whites.

801
00:40:11,375 --> 00:40:13,275
GATES: In March 2008,

802
00:40:13,344 --> 00:40:15,676
the media discovered
the fiery sermons

803
00:40:15,746 --> 00:40:19,580
of Obama's pastor,
Reverend Jeremiah Wright.

804
00:40:19,650 --> 00:40:21,948
The government
gives them the drugs,

805
00:40:22,019 --> 00:40:25,113
builds bigger prisons,
passes a 3-strike law,

806
00:40:25,189 --> 00:40:28,625
and then wants us to sing
"God Bless America"?

807
00:40:28,692 --> 00:40:31,957
No, no, no!
Not "God Bless America."

808
00:40:32,029 --> 00:40:33,656
"...Damn America!"

809
00:40:33,731 --> 00:40:36,632
I wouldn't sit in a church where
a pastor said that. Would you?

810
00:40:36,700 --> 00:40:38,497
Why does Senator Obama?

811
00:40:38,569 --> 00:40:40,127
Commitment to
the black community.

812
00:40:40,204 --> 00:40:42,138
Commitment to the black family.

813
00:40:42,206 --> 00:40:43,867
Adherence to the black
work ethic.

814
00:40:43,941 --> 00:40:45,966
If every time
we said "black,"

815
00:40:46,043 --> 00:40:48,978
if it was a church,
and those words were "white,"

816
00:40:49,046 --> 00:40:50,809
wouldn't we call
that church racist?

817
00:40:50,881 --> 00:40:53,816
GATES: Although Obama
had avoided emphasizing

818
00:40:53,884 --> 00:40:56,751
the issue of race
during the campaign,

819
00:40:56,821 --> 00:40:59,585
the media frenzy
that ensued

820
00:40:59,657 --> 00:41:01,557
forced him to confront
the topic head-on.

821
00:41:01,625 --> 00:41:05,152
The path to a more perfect Union
means acknowledging

822
00:41:05,229 --> 00:41:07,322
that what ails
the African American community

823
00:41:07,398 --> 00:41:11,164
does not just exist
in the minds of black people.

824
00:41:11,235 --> 00:41:14,568
Working together,
we can move beyond

825
00:41:14,638 --> 00:41:16,503
some of our old
racial wounds

826
00:41:16,574 --> 00:41:19,338
and that, in fact,
we have no choice.

827
00:41:19,410 --> 00:41:22,675
We have no choice if we are
to continue on the path

828
00:41:22,746 --> 00:41:26,147
of a more perfect Union.

829
00:41:26,217 --> 00:41:28,185
GATES: By reassuring
many Americans

830
00:41:28,252 --> 00:41:30,345
that he understood
both sides

831
00:41:30,421 --> 00:41:34,221
of the country's longstanding
and painful racial divide,

832
00:41:34,291 --> 00:41:37,021
Obama inspired voters
to do something

833
00:41:37,094 --> 00:41:39,756
that many considered
impossible.

834
00:41:39,830 --> 00:41:41,821
NEWSMEN: Pennsylvania
has gone to Obama.

835
00:41:41,899 --> 00:41:44,367
Senator Obama will carry
the State of Massachusetts.

836
00:41:44,435 --> 00:41:47,097
Ohio is gone for Obama.

837
00:41:47,171 --> 00:41:48,695
We can report history.

838
00:41:48,772 --> 00:41:52,799
You are looking at the 44th
President of the United States.

839
00:41:52,877 --> 00:41:54,868
The celebrations begin.

840
00:41:54,945 --> 00:41:58,540
[Cheering "Yes, we can!"]

841
00:41:58,616 --> 00:42:00,083
POWELL: We did it.

842
00:42:00,150 --> 00:42:02,414
They said we couldn't,
and we did it.

843
00:42:02,486 --> 00:42:04,147
Yeah.

844
00:42:04,221 --> 00:42:08,214
I cried.

845
00:42:08,292 --> 00:42:10,317
I still do.

846
00:42:10,394 --> 00:42:12,021
[Cheering]

847
00:42:15,099 --> 00:42:19,729
JORDAN: My eyes
filled with tears,

848
00:42:19,803 --> 00:42:22,863
but they were not
my tears.

849
00:42:22,940 --> 00:42:25,170
They were the tears
of my parents

850
00:42:25,242 --> 00:42:28,734
and my grandparents.

851
00:42:28,812 --> 00:42:33,909
They were the tears
of all of those black people

852
00:42:33,984 --> 00:42:36,817
who toted that cotton
and lifted that bale.

853
00:42:36,887 --> 00:42:38,582
Did you think
America was ready

854
00:42:38,656 --> 00:42:40,214
to elect a black
President?

855
00:42:40,291 --> 00:42:42,987
It doesn't matter.
It happened.

856
00:42:43,060 --> 00:42:45,324
[Cheering]

857
00:42:54,872 --> 00:42:57,432
Change has come
to America.

858
00:42:57,508 --> 00:42:59,169
[Cheering]

859
00:42:59,243 --> 00:43:02,440
GATES: As people all over
the world rejoiced,

860
00:43:02,513 --> 00:43:05,448
we, too, could
once again believe

861
00:43:05,516 --> 00:43:07,677
in the promise
of America.

862
00:43:07,751 --> 00:43:09,719
COBB: So there's
always been

863
00:43:09,787 --> 00:43:12,551
this double vision
of America-

864
00:43:12,623 --> 00:43:14,284
America, the land
of opportunity,

865
00:43:14,358 --> 00:43:16,292
and also America,
the land that has

866
00:43:16,360 --> 00:43:18,453
a rigid racial
hierarchy.

867
00:43:20,030 --> 00:43:22,999
What Obama's election did

868
00:43:23,067 --> 00:43:26,127
was offer the country
at least a moment

869
00:43:26,203 --> 00:43:28,137
in which it could
renew that creed,

870
00:43:28,205 --> 00:43:29,866
the land where everything
is possible.

871
00:43:29,940 --> 00:43:31,134
Congratulations,
Mr. President.

872
00:43:31,208 --> 00:43:32,368
Thank you, sir.

873
00:43:32,443 --> 00:43:34,434
[Cheering and applause]

874
00:43:43,220 --> 00:43:45,313
GATES: Against
the greatest odds,

875
00:43:45,389 --> 00:43:49,951
America sent a black man
to the White House.

876
00:43:54,598 --> 00:43:58,830
In the euphoria that followed,
some even dared to wonder

877
00:43:58,902 --> 00:44:01,268
was this the end
of racism?

878
00:44:01,338 --> 00:44:05,672
Could 500 years
of race relations

879
00:44:05,743 --> 00:44:10,806
be transformed
by the election of one man?

880
00:44:18,589 --> 00:44:22,787
The idea that one
black President ended racism-

881
00:44:22,860 --> 00:44:24,020
like...Aah!

882
00:44:24,094 --> 00:44:26,324
Like, it was just like,
that's all it takes?

883
00:44:26,397 --> 00:44:27,523
I think people
wanted to buy it.

884
00:44:27,598 --> 00:44:28,792
And there was so much good
feeling around Barack

885
00:44:28,866 --> 00:44:30,527
at that point
that we wanted to believe

886
00:44:30,601 --> 00:44:32,034
that he was--you know,
it's the extension

887
00:44:32,102 --> 00:44:33,660
of the magical negro
in the movies.

888
00:44:33,737 --> 00:44:36,365
And that good feeling
led to claims

889
00:44:36,440 --> 00:44:38,203
that somehow we had
turned a corner,

890
00:44:38,275 --> 00:44:39,970
that we were
so-called post-racial.

891
00:44:40,044 --> 00:44:42,137
America was founded
on racism.

892
00:44:42,212 --> 00:44:44,646
The only way
we get to be post-racial

893
00:44:44,715 --> 00:44:46,046
is the way that we got to be
post-dinosaur.

894
00:44:46,116 --> 00:44:47,879
You know what I mean?
Like, a meteor has to hit

895
00:44:47,951 --> 00:44:49,543
and just sort of wipe
everything out,

896
00:44:49,620 --> 00:44:51,850
and then something else
has to replace America.

897
00:44:53,457 --> 00:44:55,391
BLACKWELL: Attitudes are
improving about race.

898
00:44:55,459 --> 00:44:57,552
All the polls show it.

899
00:44:57,628 --> 00:45:00,392
The American people
actually feel better

900
00:45:00,464 --> 00:45:01,658
about people
who are different.

901
00:45:01,732 --> 00:45:03,563
They feel better
about black people.

902
00:45:03,634 --> 00:45:05,158
They have less racism.

903
00:45:05,235 --> 00:45:09,228
But those personal attitudes
don't translate into change,

904
00:45:09,306 --> 00:45:13,402
because the racism now
is institutionalized.

905
00:45:13,477 --> 00:45:14,637
It's structural.

906
00:45:15,979 --> 00:45:18,914
COBB: This African America
who is in the White House

907
00:45:18,982 --> 00:45:20,574
occurs at a point
where there's

908
00:45:20,651 --> 00:45:22,949
nearly a million black men
who are incarcerated,

909
00:45:23,020 --> 00:45:25,079
at a point where
black unemployment

910
00:45:25,155 --> 00:45:28,249
is routinely double that
of white unemployment,

911
00:45:28,325 --> 00:45:31,260
at a point where there are
all these enduring indicators

912
00:45:31,328 --> 00:45:33,660
of social, economic
inequality.

913
00:45:34,098 --> 00:45:39,092
